Bone fractures are among the most common medical conditions worldwide, requiring prompt and accurate diagnosis for effective treatment. Manual interpretation of X-ray images by radiologists can be time-consuming, error-prone, and limited by human fatigue. This project aims to develop an AI-based system for automated detection of bone fractures using image processing and deep learning techniques, specifically transfer learning.
Pre-trained convolutional neural networks (CNNs) such as VGG16, ResNet50, or EfficientNet will be fine-tuned on X-ray datasets to classify images as fractured or normal. The approach leverages existing deep models trained on large datasets (like ImageNet) and adapts them to medical imaging, significantly reducing training time and improving accuracy with limited data.
This project demonstrates how AI can assist healthcare professionals in rapid fracture detection, potentially reducing diagnostic workload, improving patient outcomes, and contributing toward intelligent medical imaging systems.
